snapshot.s: Using the example in Table 3-2, create a well-formatted, detailed business case for your project.

1.0 Introduction/Background
	The Chinese Association Dance Crew (CADC) is a collegiate competitive dance team from the University of California, Irvine.  All members of the crew are full-time UC Irvine undergraduate students who are also members of the Chinese Association club on campus.  CADC currently utilizes a website to display team announcements and upcoming events. However, the site is hardly updated, and functions more as a blog that lacks visual appeal.  The site is setup in a blog layout and contains little to no information about the team or the organization itself.  Additionally, this site was initially used to display announcements for followers--new or old members--of CADC, but in recent years, it has been used only for announcing the new team. 
Our group aims to improve the overall content of the site in regards to information, multimedia, and user experience by providing current information in a visually stunning and fully functional display that will promote the crew as well as draw interest in prospective members. 

2.0 Business Objective
	The purpose of modifying the overall layout and content of the site is to create a website that will rebrand the Chinese Association Dance Crew with revamped graphics and up-to-date information.  The reason behind redesigning the layout of the pages and adding interactive elements to each page is that accomplishing this will attract current and prospective members to visit the page and continuously return for future updates.
Another objective of this project is to implement a website that is easy to update and edit. By implementing an easy-to-use interface for administrators of the system, members will be more inclined to use and maintain the site.
Implementing these proposed changes will allow the site to become more interactive and cohesive, and will greatly improve its visual and interest appeal. 
	
3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement
	The website for the Chinese Association Dance Crew has been functioning since 2003, and was initially designed to be a blog that announces upcoming events.  However, the website has become neglected and infrequently updated.  As of now the website is only updated once a year to post the current team roster which contains limited information about the team anyways.
A website for an organization should contain information about the organization, its members, and their events, presented via an engaging interface which creates a lasting impression and entertaining experience for the viewers.  With the website in its current state, it is difficult to navigate through and  displays out-of-date graphics and information, and contains several dead or unrelated links; the login intended for members does not perform its functionality properly.  The website fails to capture people’s attention and does not provide any information about the current team. Without any updates in content or an aesthetically pleasing layout, the current site does not serve any purpose in representing and promoting the Chinese Association Dance Crew.  By addressing these issues, the site will attract more viewers and become an effective platform for communicating updates and announcements to fans and other visitors to the site. 

4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints
Time
Access to member information, pictures, videos
Resource dependence on the CADC members
Approval by the CADC team

	As of now, the main concern for this project is our unfamiliarity with HTML; our team will need to obtain a sufficient understanding of HTML to produce the desired product. Another constraint for the project is time. With only seven weeks to complete the project, our group will need to obtain a significant amount of information and data from the CADC team to make the site fully functional with all the needed information incorporated. Without sufficient information about the current team, past team, alumni and other details regarding these groups within CADC, we may not have enough content to provide a complete informational website. 
	Current assumptions for the project are that we will have administrative access to the current site, our approach to revamp the website is approved by the CADC team, and that CADC is willing to provide us with any and all information needed for the project. 

5.0 Analysis of Option and Recommendation
Dance teams utilize a form of a website, whether it is a blog or an informational site, to advertise themselves, showcase their achievements and their members, and connect with their followers. It is important for the team to distinguish themselves through images and videos used throughout the website in order to enhance their image. Currently, the Chinese Association Dance Crew website is a simple blog mainly used to post basic announcements. The blog, however, lacks any information regarding the dance team and its members. Optionally, the website could consist of team information as well as a blog that can be directed towards a fan-based audience. In addition, social media applications such as Twitter, Facebook, Google Plus and potentially Instagram may also be integrated to reach a greater audience. We can build on top of the blog based website or create a brand new website and integrate the blog.
	A huge part of the Chinese Association Dance Crew is the alumni base and team named Chinese Association Old School, ChAOS for short. Many of the graduated members are still active and still partake in events with the current team. There can be several additions to the website that describe who they are and what they are. These pages may include images and videos as well as textual information about the alumni. As they are part of the CADC family, it adds to the history of the team and adds to the description of the Chinese Association Dance Crew. We may include or exclude this section as the team see’s fit in representing CADC. 
	A main concern for this website is user interaction. One possibility to increase the site’s appeal is to have a complete section for the supporters of CADC. Fans could make their own accounts and  “attend” events and raise support for each event. Statistics such as “Top Supporters” could be displayed to encourage users to participate. Further rewards such as actual prizes will be determined by the team. This section could be expanded in the future depending on how effective it is. 

6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements
1. Establish communication with CADC and notify them of the project and our goals
2. Familiarize with web environment, learn HTML, CSS, javascript and any other programming languages that will help us in developing the website and obtain any web design software needed. 
3. Gather information and multimedia about the team, team members and announcements
4. Create layouts and page contents for the site
5. Program layouts and fill out page contents for created layouts and pages
6. Implement other features suggested by CADC or users, if they add to the user experience or cohesiveness of the website

7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis
There are no foreseeable costs for this project. We will be using and modifying the current  website, so the domain is already paid for by CADC. However, in the case that the administrator for the current site is unreachable, we may have to purchase a domain for the development of this project. Also, all multimedia used in the website will either be taken by us or provided to us for free by the team. 

8.0 Schedule Estimate
	In order to ensure that the project is successful, we first need to familiarize ourselves with domains and the publishing process within the first week. After determining the basic logistics, we then need to gather a majority of the information that will be implemented in the site. This will roughly take 1-2 weeks and will ensure that the site has the basic information needed to be sufficient. The following 1-2 weeks needs to be dedicated to setting the basic structure and layout of the website. After the website is up and running with a basic layout and minimal functionality, we will spend the remaining time implementing any and all extraneous features to the site. Ultimately, we plan to finish this project within 7 weeks. 

9.0 Potential Risks
Insufficient resource
HTML knowledge
Failure to get access to current site
Failure to implement some features due to time constraint
Not limited in creative bounds, we may run into difficulties with decisions on what represents the team best and what we think may be a good implementation 

	There are several risks involved with the project, the foremost being our lack of experience in HTML. We have proposed several complex features, such as the integration of third party applications, which may be out of our scope and difficult to finish within the allotted time. Other risks such as current site access and proper representation are minute problems that can be worked around.
